
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `factor` baraye tajziyeh adad sahih be a’daade avval (prime numbers) estefade mishavad. Yani adad ra be soorate zarbi az adadhaaye avval neshun midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `factor adad` --> 🔢 Tajziyeh adad morede nazar. Agar chand adad bedehi, hame ra tajziyeh mikonad.
    🔹 `factor` (bedune hich gozine) --> ⌨️ Az vorudi standard (keyboard) adad migirad va tajziyeh mikonad. Ba Ctrl+D mitavani be barnamé befahmani ke vorudi tamom shode ast.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ factor 12
    12: 2 2 3

    🔹 Adad 12 ra be zarb 2 * 2 * 3 tajziyeh kard.

    $ factor 36 48 100
    36: 2 2 3 3
    48: 2 2 2 2 3
    100: 2 2 5 5

    🔹 Chand adad ra hamzaman tajziyeh mikonad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ factor
    17
    17: 17
    25
    25: 5 5
    ^D

    🔹 Dar in mesal, `factor` az keyboard vorudi gerefte va tajziyeh karde ast.  Ba Ctrl+D vorudi ra tamam kardim.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `factor` command is used to decompose an integer into its prime factors. It expresses the number as a product of prime numbers.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `factor number` --> 🔢 Factorizes the specified number. If you provide multiple numbers, it factorizes all of them.
    🔹 `factor` (without any options) --> ⌨️ Reads numbers from standard input (keyboard) and factorizes them.  You can use Ctrl+D to signal the end of input.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ factor 12
    12: 2 2 3

    🔹 Factorizes the number 12 into the product 2 * 2 * 3.

    $ factor 36 48 100
    36: 2 2 3 3
    48: 2 2 2 2 3
    100: 2 2 5 5

    🔹 Factorizes multiple numbers simultaneously.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ factor
    17
    17: 17
    25
    25: 5 5
    ^D

    🔹 In this example, `factor` takes input from the keyboard and factorizes it. We terminated the input using Ctrl+D.
